          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">When it comes right=
 down to it, national political conventions are television shows, nothing m=
ore and nothing less. Sure, there are 20,000 people in the hall, and the ba=
lloon drop is always a blast, but every one of the delegates and other gran=
dees are already voting for <b>Kamala Harris</b>, so entertaining them only=
 matters to the extent it makes the week of nightly broadcasts in primetime=
 more riveting, highly rated, and successful in accomplishing other goals t=
hat are more tangible and measurable: reaching a bunch of people who don=E2=
=80=99t normally pay attention to politics, raking in campaign contribution=
s, and recruiting new foot soldiers to the cause. And it=E2=80=99s in terms=
 of these quotidian metrics that the Democratic convocation in Chicago last=
 week was truly killer.<br/><br/>To give you a sense of how the political o=
perative class assesses a
convention, consider this: When I sat down late Thursday night after Harris=
=E2=80=99s speech with <b>Patrick Gaspard</b>=E2=80=94<b>Barack Obama</b>=
=E2=80=99s former political director and ambassador to South Africa and now=
 C.E.O. of the Center for American Progress Action Fund=E2=80=94to tape the=
 most recent episode of the <i>Impolitic</i> podcast, the first words out o=
f his mouth had to do with volunteers. When <b>Joe Biden</b> was the party=
=E2=80=99s nominee, he noted, the campaign had <i>thousands </i>of them; no=
w it has <i>hundreds of thousands</i>. As Harris campaign chair <b>Jen O=E2=
=80=99Malley Dillon </b>laid it out in an =E2=80=9Cinterested parties=E2=80=
=9D memo a few days later: =E2=80=9CHeaded into the convention, our campaig=
n hosted a weekend of action, and volunteers completed 10,000 shifts and co=
ntacted over 1 million voters. The convention itself helped build on that m=
omentum, generating nearly 200,000 new volunteer shifts.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>=
The other numbers coming out of the convention were just as striking.
Harris=E2=80=99s speech drew a whopping 28.9 million viewers, millions more=
 than <b>Donald Trump</b>=E2=80=99s rambling walk in the woods at the Repub=
lican convention last month. Over the weekend, Team K announced it had rais=
ed a staggering $82 million last week, bringing the total it=E2=80=99s coll=
ected in a little more than a month since KDH became the <i>de facto </i>no=
minee to $540 million, =E2=80=9Ca record for any campaign in history.=E2=80=
=9D<br/><br/>And yet, as <b>Dan Pfeiffer</b> wryly observed in his <i><u><a=
 href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktxcl=
JLZ0dSaS05NGEyMDV3eEJiczZJLXVxbz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWVzc2FnZWJve=
G5ld3MuY29tL3Avd2h5LXlvdS1zaG91bGRudC1wYW5pYy1hYm91dC1yZms_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWdu=
PVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4OCUyRjI1JTJGMjQ=
lMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1UaGUrQmVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUk=
lCRVJTKyUyODglMkYyMCUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwM=
jZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJh=
IiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoxMDA4MDcyfQ/152b=
b00d1f409d1cd40d2deaf6dbcb592850a31e1ef8d1c231b68057f36bc986" style=3D"colo=
r:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">Message Box<=
/a></u></i> Substack, even after =E2=80=9Ca month-long run of unabated good=
 news=E2=80=9D and a kickass convention, =E2=80=9Cbecause we are Democrats,=
 we are now waiting for the inevitable turn of the worm.=E2=80=9D Pfeiffer =
was addressing the
reflexive =E2=80=9CHow screwed are we?=E2=80=9D freak-out among many Democr=
ats over <b>Robert F. Kennedy</b>=E2=80=99s decision to quit the race and e=
ndorse Trump. (Not screwed at all, was Dan=E2=80=99s answer, and plenty of =
smart data wizards agree.)<br/><br/>But the truth is that, among top strate=
gists and tacticians in both parties, there=E2=80=99s a clear consensus abo=
ut the state of the race despite how well Chicago went for Harris and her p=
arty: It is simply back to being a <i>tie</i> again. With all that=E2=80=99=
s occurred since Harris=E2=80=99s elevation to the top of the ticket, inclu=
ding her basically flawless performance as a candidate, she now holds a sma=
ll lead, well inside the margin of error, both nationally and in most of th=
e battleground states. And if you go back to 2020, Biden was ahead by six t=
o <i>eight </i>points nationally in all of the battleground states. Because=
 polling has consistently failed to capture Trump=E2=80=99s support in pres=
idential election years, and because of the structural
advantage conferred on the G.O.P. by the Electoral College, political insid=
ers share a common view that, in order to prevail, Harris=E2=80=99s numbers=
 are going to have to be somewhere in the neighborhood of Biden=E2=80=99s l=
ast time around=E2=80=94and even then, she=E2=80=99d likely beat Trump by j=
ust a <i>hair</i>. <br/><br/>With the arrival of <b>David Plouffe</b> and O=
bama pollster and focus group impresario <b>David Binder</b>, Team K is sti=
ll in the process of tuning and cranking up a state-of-the-art data and ana=
lytics operation (which the campaign hadn=E2=80=99t placed as much emphasis=
 on when Biden was behind the wheel). Between that work in progress and the=
 usual post-convention, end-of-summer noise in the data, there=E2=80=99s a =
widespread sense that the campaign won=E2=80=99t have a detailed, fine-grai=
ned handle on the state of the race=E2=80=94and its implications in terms o=
f the genuinely plausible paths to 270 electoral voters=E2=80=94until after=
 Labor Day.<br/><br/>On the Republican side, the picture seems
considerably clearer. At a number of private briefings during the G.O.P. co=
nvention in Milwaukee, Trump pollster <b>Tony Fabrizio</b> boasted (in a fi=
t of post-assassination-attempt brio) that his boss had so many paths to 27=
0 that the campaign had given up counting after getting to two dozen, but t=
hen acknowledged that Trump=E2=80=99s cleanest, simplest path was this: hol=
d the states he won in 2020 and then add Georgia and Pennsylvania to the Re=
publican column=E2=80=94which got him to 270 without winning Arizona, Nevad=
a, Michigan, Wisconsin, or any other state that Biden carried. And where, p=
ray tell, is the Trump campaign spending the lion=E2=80=99s share of its do=
ugh right now? Bingo: GA and PA.<br/><br/>All of which reinforces the view =
that Pennsylvania is likely to be the tipping-point state this year, just l=
ike it was in 2020, when, please recall, the entire country was still waiti=
ng and holding its breath for its final result five days after Election Nig=
ht. And if you sit down with any
Democratic Party operative and give them one drink, they=E2=80=99ll also te=
ll you that the concept of winning Pennsylvania with a Black woman at the t=
op of the ticket gives them the heebie-jeebies=E2=80=94which is why so many=
